[[File:Peacekeeper - simulated missile and canister test 1.jpg|thumb|Simulated missile and canister test at Jackass Flats]]
'''Jackass Flats''' is a shallow alluvial basin located in the southwest portion of the [[Nevada National Security Site]] in [[Nye County, Nevada]]. The area lies east of [[Yucca Mountain]], south of the [[Calico Hills]] and [[Shoshone Mountain]] and northwest of [[Skull Mountain (Nevada)|Skull Mountain]]. The valley drains to the southwest via the Tonopah and Fortymile washes into the [[Amargosa Valley]] across [[US Route 95]] at [[Amargosa Valley, Nevada|Amargosa Valley]]. The "flat" covers an area of approximately {{convert|120|mi2}} and ranges in elevation from about {{convert|2800|ft|abbr=on}} just north of US 95 to {{convert|4000|ft|abbr=on}} at the mountain bases to the north and east.<ref>''Beatty, Nevada–California,'' 30x60 Minute Topographic Quadrangle, USGS, 1986</ref>

It is located mostly within [[Area 25 (Nevada National Security Site)|Area 25]] and extends into [[Area 14 (NTS)|Area 14]] and [[Area 26 (NTS)|Area 26]].

It was the test site of nuclear-powered rocket engines during project [[Project Rover]] and [[NERVA]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clark|first1=John Drury|title=Ignition! An Informal History of Liquid Rocket Propellants|date=1972|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=0-8135-0725-1|page=109|url=http://www.sciencemadness.org/library/books/ignition.pdf|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>

